{"kind":"article","seeAlsoSections":[{"title":"Events","identifiers":["doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/RiseSetTimes","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/Eclipses","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/Seasons","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/LunarEclipse","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/GlobalSolarEclipse","doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/LocalSolarEclipse"],"generated":true,"anchor":"Events"}],"abstract":[{"type":"text","text":"Calculate equinoxes, solstices, planetary apsides, elongations, and transits."}],"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"type":"heading","anchor":"Overview","level":2,"text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"AstronomyKit provides calculations for seasonal events (equinoxes and solstices), planetary orbital events (apsides), elongation and visibility, and rare transits of Mercury and Venus.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Equinoxes-and-Solstices","level":2,"text":"Equinoxes and Solstices"},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Get-All-Seasons-for-a-Year","level":3,"text":"Get All Seasons for a Year"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let seasons = try Seasons.forYear(2025)","","print(\"🌸 Spring: \\(seasons.marchEquinox)\")","print(\"☀️ Summer: \\(seasons.juneSolstice)\")","print(\"🍂 Autumn: \\(seasons.septemberEquinox)\")","print(\"❄️ Winter: \\(seasons.decemberSolstice)\")"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Iterate-Over-Events","level":3,"text":"Iterate Over Events"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let seasons = try Seasons.forYear(2025)","","for (name, time) in seasons.allEvents {","    print(\"\\(name): \\(time)\")","}"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Planetary-Apsides","level":2,"text":"Planetary Apsides"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Apsides are the closest (perihelion) and farthest (aphelion) points in a planet’s orbit around the Sun.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Find-Next-Planetary-Apsis","level":3,"text":"Find Next Planetary Apsis"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let apsis = try CelestialBody.mars.searchApsis(after: .now)","print(\"\\(apsis.kind.solarName) at \\(apsis.time)\")","print(\"Distance: \\(apsis.distanceAU) AU\")"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"All-Apsides-in-a-Range","level":3,"text":"All Apsides in a Range"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let apsides = try CelestialBody.earth.apsides(","    from: AstroTime(year: 2025, month: 1, day: 1),","    to: AstroTime(year: 2030, month: 1, day: 1)",")","","for apsis in apsides {","    print(\"\\(apsis.kind.solarName): \\(apsis.time)\")","}"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Elongation-and-Visibility","level":2,"text":"Elongation and Visibility"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Elongation is the angular separation between a planet and the Sun. This determines when planets are best visible.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Current-Elongation","level":3,"text":"Current Elongation"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let elong = try CelestialBody.venus.elongation(at: .now)","print(\"Venus is \\(elong.angle)° from the Sun\")","print(\"Visibility: \\(elong.visibility.name) star\")","","if elong.visibility == .evening {","    print(\"Look for Venus after sunset\")","} else {","    print(\"Look for Venus before sunrise\")","}"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Maximum-Elongation","level":3,"text":"Maximum Elongation"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Find when a planet reaches greatest separation from the Sun:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let maxElong = try CelestialBody.mercury.searchMaxElongation(after: .now)","print(\"Mercury max elongation: \\(maxElong.angle)°\")","print(\"Date: \\(maxElong.time)\")","print(\"\\(maxElong.visibility.name) star\")"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"This is especially useful for Mercury and Venus, which are never far from the Sun.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Illumination-and-Magnitude","level":2,"text":"Illumination and Magnitude"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Calculate the visual brightness and illumination of planets.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Current-Illumination","level":3,"text":"Current Illumination"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let illum = try CelestialBody.venus.illumination(at: .now)","print(\"Magnitude: \\(illum.magnitude)\")","print(\"Phase: \\(Int(illum.phaseFraction * 100))% illuminated\")","print(\"Distance from Sun: \\(illum.helioDistance) AU\")"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Saturns-Rings","level":3,"text":"Saturn’s Rings"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"For Saturn, illumination includes ring tilt:"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let saturn = try CelestialBody.saturn.illumination(at: .now)","print(\"Ring tilt: \\(saturn.ringTilt)°\")"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Peak-Magnitude","level":3,"text":"Peak Magnitude"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Find when a planet reaches maximum brightness:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let peak = try CelestialBody.venus.searchPeakMagnitude(after: .now)","print(\"Venus brightest at \\(peak.time)\")","print(\"Magnitude: \\(peak.magnitude)\")"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Planetary-Transits","level":2,"text":"Planetary Transits"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Transits occur when Mercury or Venus passes between Earth and the Sun."}]},{"type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Transits are rare events. Mercury transits occur about 13 times per century, while Venus transits occur in pairs separated by over a century.","type":"text"}]}],"style":"note","name":"Note"},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Find-Next-Transit","level":3,"text":"Find Next Transit"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let transit = try Transit.search(body: .mercury, after: .now)","print(\"Transit date: \\(transit.peak)\")","print(\"Duration: \\(transit.duration \/ 60) minutes\")"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Transit-Timing","level":3,"text":"Transit Timing"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["print(\"Start (first contact): \\(transit.start)\")","print(\"Peak (mid-transit): \\(transit.peak)\")","print(\"End (last contact): \\(transit.finish)\")","print(\"Minimum separation: \\(transit.separation) arcmin\")"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"All-Transits-in-a-Range","level":3,"text":"All Transits in a Range"},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["\/\/ Find all Mercury transits in the next 50 years","let transits = try Transit.transits(","    body: .mercury,","    from: .now,","    to: .now.addingDays(365 * 50)",")","","for transit in transits {","    print(\"\\(transit.body.name) transit: \\(transit.peak)\")","}"]},{"type":"heading","anchor":"Angular-Separation","level":2,"text":"Angular Separation"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Calculate the angle between a body and the Sun:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let angle = try CelestialBody.jupiter.angleFromSun(at: .now)","print(\"Jupiter is \\(angle)° from the Sun\")","","\/\/ Opposition occurs when angle ≈ 180°","if angle > 170 {","    print(\"Jupiter is near opposition!\")","}"]}],"kind":"content"}],"variants":[{"traits":[{"interfaceLanguage":"swift"}],"paths":["\/documentation\/astronomykit\/seasonsandevents"]}],"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit\/SeasonsAndEvents","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/AstronomyKit\/documentation\/AstronomyKit"]]},"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"patch":0,"major":0},"sections":[],"metadata":{"modules":[{"name":"AstronomyKit"}],"roleHeading":"Article","title":"Seasons and Events","role":"article"},"references":{"doc://AstronomyKit/documentation/AstronomyKit":{"url":"\